Songs of WaterDeep  

by Ashale'n Dervise

The CALL
(Written for the festivale of Life to bolster the peoples spirits during the time of undead)

Hearken now unto my call     
For Waterdeep shall never fall,  
  You hold in yourselves a strength untold, 
Your hearts are brave, your spirits bold. 

We took this land from Orcs and Trolls,
Built a city 'tween river and shoals.
Folk of the 'Deep are a hardy and true,   Many and great were the trials they knew.

For we are the people of the Deep,   
To take a piece of us, won't come cheap!   
We will take a bite,  then hold on tight, 
Our tenacity will win the fight! 
We are the people of the Deep!!  

The Lords and the Mages work for a Hope,
To find the way our  'Deep will cope.
By sharpened blade or fiercesome spell,
The Evil and undead they seek to quell.

The Gods themselves once walked our street,
What's a few undead we must defeat?
A dragon was killed on the High road here,
In the face of trouble we just persevere!

For we are the people of the Deep,   
To take a piece of us, won't come cheap!   
We will take a bite,  then hold on tight, 
Our stubbornness will win the fight! 
We are the people of the Deep!!  

With the turning of the tide,
Once more must you decide.
Will you let the darkness win,
Or take a stand that's genuine?

Trust in those who can a difference make,
To rid the wards of  evils outbreak.
Soon again will our city Splendid be,
A sight for all of Faerun to see..

For we are the people of the Deep,   
To take a piece of us, won't come cheap!   
We will take a bite,  then hold on tight, 
Our stubbornness will win the fight! 
We are the people of the Deep!!

WHITE WASHED SPLENDOR

Ashale'n  Dervise

 There lies in the Land a city of  Splendor,
Its towers rise high to the sky,
But hidden beneath the glitter and  glamour,
Is the grime of the white washed lie.

While the nobles they hide at the party
And  the Lords stay safe behind masks.
The slavers they Infest the city,
Taking any who hinder their tasks.

 The guards in their finery walk the beats,
Proclaiming the laws of the 'Deep
While the poor are left out on the streets,
To beg or to steal for their keep.

 Temples grand, of marble and stone,
Serving the people for solace of souls,
They expect all to tithe to the bone,
To fill up their coffer bowls.

  The Lord in the open  is only a token
Of the Powers that rule on high
Under the streets, lies a threat  to be broken,
Like an evil disease, that spreads nigh.

Beauty is seen by those who are blind,  
For the city  is whitewashed in Lime,
Look in the corners, and see what you find
The true powers lie with those who do crime.

Truth and Corruption
By Ashale'n Dervise

Listen, listen if you dare
The Lord of the castle does not care.
Slavers take your children, Slavers take your wife,
Slavers in the city causing strife.

Tell me, tell me, can you hear.
The cries of the people living in fear.
Guards in the city, Guards in the street,
Guards chasing victims of slaver deceit.

Hear me, hear me, did you know?
The Lord's been fooled by slavers below.
Lies from the slavers, Lies from the spies, 
Lies about merchants their gold buys.

Run, run, can you keep pace?
The truth has now taken on a different face.
Corruption in the halls, Corruption in the 'Deep,
Corruption at the city core does outward seep.

Pray, pray, if you can
Innocents suffer by the slavers plan.
Justice is lacking, justice is blind,
Justice is twisted by the vigilante mind.

Songs of the Darker side
by Ashale'n Dervise

SHADOW

Shadows come and Shadows go
A little light will quell them so,
The Shadow better watch it's tread,
Lest the darkness  lose it's dread.

Shadow soon may fall from grace, 
Revealing then the dark ones face.
No power over those who wait,
Exposing them to evils fate.

The Lords minions careless grow
Corrupt in powers fat and slow
Shadows powers fade away,
With the coming of the day.

Guard the rear and guard the fore,
Know the Shadows wanting more.
If the Shadow knows what's best,
It will steal back unto it's nest.
 
Will the Shadows Lord  protect it there.
Or kill it with an evil stare?
Know the Shadow has failed too,
   It brings not darkness to me and you.

So let the light on shadows fall
Til the dawn brings hope to all.
The Shadow, fear will know instead,
When the Lord wants Him dead.

**********************************************Shadows in the Night

Does the Shadow by the wall.
Have a moving form at all?
Is it just the mind laid bare,
To see danger lurking there?

Creeping closer, hearts are beating,
Movement seen from corners fleeting.
Is there really something seen,
What does the apprehension mean?

In the night a blade clears sheath,
Does the Shadow now have teeth?
Will the bite cut deep and strong
Leaving lifeblood to last not long?

Will you see the light of day 
Can the shadow stop its play,
Is it only one's own fear 
That lets the darkness rule here
 
Will the ever pounding voice,
Leave the mind with out a choice?
And veil all in shadows dark
Or will the light of truth give spark?

HELM'S LAMENT

By Ashale'n Dervise

Where hides the priest who is Calis named,
Who has  caused my temple to be ashamed?
Why does his suit of gleaming plate,
Cast a yellow pallor of late?

Why  does not his duty tend,
To protect those who could not fend?
Does he justify  those left behind
By seeking battle of another kind?

Does he spend his time from sight,
With the ladies of the night?
Why leave her lying without pay,
When morning brings the light of day?

Will the priest a coward stay
And earn the wrath that come his way?
Or will he prove his heart is not marred
And give his all to protect  and guard?

Common Primer of the Elven language

Compiled by Ashale'n Dervise


Lesson 1 - pronunciation

Vowel Sounds:
Unlike common, where there are several different ways to pronounce vowels, Elven vowels are more consistent. Notice there is no sound for "uh" as in just.

A (ah) like ball
E (eh) like excellent
I (ee) like bee 
O (oh) like old
U (oo) like exhume
Y (yih) like yippie


Diphthongs:
There are only a few diphthongs in Elven. Start with the first vowel sound, then slide into the next. All other vowel sounds are pronounced separately.
ai ("eye,")
au ("ow")
ei ("ay")
iu ("eyew," )
oi ("oye)
ui ("we") 
If there is an "e" at the end of the word, say it! There's no such thing as the "silent e."


C: This sound exists only as a "K," but is frequently translated to "C" when writing in common letters.The soft "C" sound is always written "S." 
 
HW: wh, as in where 

G: always hard, like growl.  

NG: Pronounced at the back of your head, as one sound.  

S: Pronounce it quickly

SS Any consonant that is doubled gets pronounced twice. So "esse" would be ehs-seh (like essay)

R Usually trill it a little.  

SH As in wish. 

TH There are two sounds for this: one hard (as in thank), one soft (as in then).  Non-elves have a hard time telling the two apart, and writing it in common provides no helpful hint as to which is which. 

X Pronounce as a K and S together. 

Stresses
 Elven has few visual clues on which syllable to stress. Yet stress is very important for true elvish. Relatively few humans ever master the proper inflections.

` is generally the separation between compound words, of which elvish has several. Usually the first syllable after the ` is stressed. 
' denotes a stress on the syllable right before it. It is also used to separate vowels which would otherwise create a combined sound. 

 

Pluralize a word end with "ra" or "in" depending on how it sounds.  
words ending in er (eg. healer) use ven, Words ending in ing (eg. Running) use ith.
Words ending in the possesive (ie John's, Paul's) use 'ka (eg:  
Toraan'ka)

The Ballad of Broken Arrows
by Aszune Whisperwind

Was on grim an autumn's day,
near the town of Waterdeep
that two friends long from home
this day her gates would keep.

The hour was past midday yet,
As they wandered out
And behind them, deep and low,
The city's horn would sound

They nay knew what it was
that made the horn so blow
and so they travelled on
from here to hitherto.

And so they came to the great place
where caravans oft leave
and from the trees rustled sounds
but the sounds were brief.

On they pressed, not knowing still
what fate for them would hold
and it was at Long Road's bridge
that danger did unfold.

Only a straggler, first they thought
of hobgoblin's thronging mass
but soon, they saw, it was too much -
this way they could not pass.

Here first a stand they made,
Exchanging shaft for shaft
of many arrow, long and fine
as opposed to goblin craft.

Many fell, but more still came
swarming down the way
and so, at last, they had to flee
back with the waning day.

Down the road and further still
there flight it would them lead
while all the way, the goblin's wrath
behind them, would not cede.

Finally the gate in sight!
Wounds already grim.
Yet the gate, tight was it locked
And so the spirits dim.

"Let us in, we come as friends!"
they shouted up in need.
"Alas, we cannot! You must hold!"
came from the city's keep.

And so they turned to face the horde
Their spirits dim and low
But what choice did they have?
Again they pulled the bow.

Arrows sung, spells were cast
And forth the battle raged
And so the fighting swept around
In blood and death engaged.

Bell-clear rang the elven voice,
And high the hin did shout.
For again, wave after wave
Goblin hordes they'd rout.

Yet their wounds were also grave
and many arrows stuck
From their clothes, cloak and shield
Soon they'd be out of luck.

When 12 times 12 the count did say,
of foes slain in fight
finally, a voice would ring:
"Inside! Now do your flight!"

And on them inside would look
The magister of gate's guard
"You have done well! Hero's true!
You fought here brave and hard."

"Henceforth shall you be friends of this
our city beloved much.
For let all know, that we do praise
Deeds of honour such."

"You excelled in battle here
and held off much foe.
Gave us time to gather force
To rally pike and bow."

"Now go with ease, you are free."
To them he then did say.
And so they went, with bruises much
But proud on on their way.

Gelcur was the little man,
Small only in height
For few match him in bravery
comes it to such a fight.

Aszne then was the elven maid,
Lady of a dwarf's hall
touched by the Moonbow, was her hand
to lead her foes to fall.

And so they went, on on their way
as the minstrel sings.
And maybe, one day, who knows?
More tales of them he brings.

The Tale of the Huntress

Written by Ashalen Dervise In the city of Waterdeep 

In Waterdeep heroes are made not by the tales told but by the deeds that are done . This is the story of one such group of heroes and the Lady who inspired them all. 

The Huntress: conceived in violence, raised with love, immersed in sorrow and driven with vengeance. 

PRELUDE 

Having come to Waterdeep to seek a place in society for herself, the Huntress was soon taken into custody by the city guard. Keeping her for days, it was finally ascertained that She was, indeed, not a threat to the city. She was released to do as she pleased, within the law, In the city. 
Seeking a purpose in life, she went about the daily business of living. 
One evening as she walked down the street, she saw a child nabbed by two men who then fled into the sewers. Concerned, she followed them. Quietly, like a shadow herself, she crept unseen behind them. They met with a third man, who held two women in chains. They waited for something. Soon, materializing from the shadows, came four, ebony skinned elves. These could only be Drow. It was apparent that the men were here to sell the women and child to them. 
The Huntress was overcome with rage, the three men and four drow lay dead before they realized what was happening. The Huntress came to her senses among their bodies, the women and child having the good sense to run when they had the chance. She left the scene of the carnage calmly. 
In the weeks to come the drow dared to the walk the streets of Waterdeep and into the Dripping Dagger itself to offer a reward of one thousand crowns for her head. Assassins stalked her. 
She chose to take the fight to them, with a group gathered for the purpose. They tracked them into a rarely traveled area, where they were able to ambush a drow raiding party that had come to deal with the local slavers. Ten drow including a priestess of Lloth, and many slavers died that night. 
Through her investigations the Huntress learned that the slavers in Waterdeep were called the Xanther, they had been dealing with the drow for many years. She had her purpose now. To strike a crippling blow to the slave trade in Waterdeep while hunting down and killing as many of the dark elves as she could... until they were in Waterdeep no more 

CHAPTER 1 

Black Archers Bride: loving widow driven to revenge upon her husbands killers. 
Trove Lords Knight: freed slave, stalwart companion, mercenary for hire. 
Illmaters Servant: Cautious, a man possessed 

The Huntress acquired information that a meeting would take place between the Xanthers guild and the drow discuss an exchange slaves for gold. These four then went into the sewers to spy upon the slavers exchange. The Knight and the Servant hid themselves nearby while the Bride and the Huntress crept close enough to overhear the details. Thinking themselves successful after a close call, being almost caught, they retreated to the surface. There to make plans to interrupt the exchange. The exchange was to take place in one of the crypts within the City of the Dead, four slaves for 2000 gold, in two ten days. 
Strategy was discussed, The area of the exchange was a small crypt and maneuvering would be difficult. There would be three from the guild and four Drow with the four slaves they would try to free. 


More help was recruited. 

Arrow of Justice: silent and swift, a man of mystery 
Mystras Vicktor: a mage, young and idealistic 


The door to the crypt, was barred from the inside and the Huntress had to enter via another way to open the door. Arriving late they were seen, and a battle ensued. Justice was dealt with a quick hand and hard blows. When the slavers were dead the count was tallied and two of their own lay dead. The Trove Lords Knight and Mystra's Viktor their life's blood spilt on the floor. Only one slave of the four had survived the fight. Breaking his chains and gathering their dead companions they returned with him into the air above. 
Two carried the fallen to the Plinth, while the others brought along the freed slave. He became ill during the trek and had to be helped. Once at the Plinth, the Servant pleaded with his superior for the return of the fallen companions souls. The money gathered from the slavers was donated to the temple for the spells required to allow their souls to return. Mystra's Viktor returned at once but The Trove Lords Knight tarried a short while. 
During this time, when the Priest was weakest from his casting, the slave, freed from the Drow was asked his name and he started laughing. Shouting something unintelligible, he transformed into a Drow assassin bent on the destruction of the Huntress. A fight ensued, and Mystra's Viktor again fell but was quickly revived this time, the assassin was vanquished. It seemed they were in truth seen at the previous meeting and that the Drow had changed the exchange, into a plot to try to kill the Huntress.

In Waterdeep heroes are made not by the tales told but by the deeds that are done . This is the story of one such group of heroes and the Lady who inspired them all.

Having come to Waterdeep to seek a place in society for herself, the Huntress was soon taken into custody by the city guard. Keeping her for days, it was finally ascertained that She was, indeed, not a threat to the city. She was released to do as she pleased, within the law, In the city. 
Seeking a purpose in life, she went about the daily business of living. 
One evening as she walked down the street, she saw a child nabbed by two men who then fled into the sewers. Concerned, she followed them. Quietly, like a shadow herself, she crept unseen behind them. They met with a third man, who held two women in chains. They waited for something. Soon, materializing from the shadows, came four, ebony skinned elves. These could only be Drow. It was apparent that the men were here to sell the women and child to them. 
The Huntress was overcome with rage, the three men and four drow lay dead before they realized what was happening. The Huntress came to her senses among their bodies, the women and child having the good sense to run when they had the chance. She left the scene of the carnage calmly. 
In the weeks to come the drow dared to the walk the streets of Waterdeep and into the Dripping Dagger itself to offer a reward of one thousand crowns for her head. Assassins stalked her. 
She chose to take the fight to them, with a group gathered for the purpose. They tracked them into a rarely traveled area, where they were able to ambush a drow raiding party that had come to deal with the local slavers. Ten drow including a priestess of Lloth, and many slavers died that night. 
Through her investigations the Huntress learned that the slavers in Waterdeep were called the Xanther, they had been dealing with the drow for many years. She had her purpose now. To strike a crippling blow to the slave trade in Waterdeep while hunting down and killing as many of the dark elves as she could... until they were in Waterdeep no more

Illmaters Servant: Cautious, a man possessed

Thinking themselves successful after a close call, being almost caught, they retreated to the surface. There to make plans to interrupt the exchange. The exchange was to take place in one of the crypts within the City of the Dead, four slaves for 2000 gold, in two ten days. 
Strategy was discussed, The area of the exchange was a small crypt and maneuvering would be difficult. There would be three from the guild and four Drow with the four slaves they would try to free.

Jacho's Song
By Ashale'n Dervise
 

Gather my friends, and to me an ear Lend,
For I  now tell you the tale of Jacho Send.
Twas' Algarond that gave him birth, though soon was stole away,
To Zhentil Keep was he sold, by Wizards come from Thay.

He was raised, to be a slave, for a Master errands ran,
Forbidden was He to speak a word to any other man.
Fourteen years lived He this way, beatings were his lot,
Til' the day He beat back,  killed his master on the spot.

Freed he did, the other slaves, and burned the tower down, 
Never looking back again, he escaped that hellish town.
Guarding for a caravan, to Waterdeep did come,
There again did errands do, to make a tidy sum.

To Llork town, he chose to go, adventure for to find,
There found himself in trouble, with evil,  Zhentish  kind. 
To Loudwater he quickly fled, and work he found to do,
But curious he wandered off and trouble found him too.

Into the city dungeon, he wandered to and fro,
He found a sight, he had not seen, and chose to closer go.
A Tanari  beast, with vultures head,  drew him near with magic,
Proceeded then, to rip his throat, death then came most tragic.

But the Gods yet had a plan , returned him to this plane,
Raised by a priest , who pity took, in Illmater's name.
 He gather the few things he owned, and to Waterdeep did head,
 On the road, there bandits met, was  beaten, robbed and left for dead.

Reduced to rags, and copperless, nothing to his name,
He begged, to keep his belly fed, until a patron came.
A hundred crowns did Jarlen give, afforded him a new start,
Then in Waterdeep went He to work, so he could get his part.

When he spoke, to rid the town, of evil in the place,
Enemies were drawn to him, he could not show his face.
To the sewers, he was lured, by one who would have him dead,
One who cared, warned "make amends" or you'll lose your head.


Upon the road to Anarouch, a bandit king, He met, 
Fighting for his life he fled, north to Olamaa, nearly spent. 
A friend he meets in town there, by a commoner, is attacked, 
Defending thus, they kill the man, incurring  Zhentish wrath.  

Then was taken by the Zhents, to be tried for crimes committed,
Standing trial, their case presented, wits against opponent pitted.
 Executed, was his friend, because he magic's used.
All possessions confiscated, poor again, is not amused.

Forced by need, since he was broke, to toil for the Zhent,
Saved their lives, but no rewards, were willing to be spent.
The bandit king, gave him work, a chance to return  Zhentish favor,
Acquired knowledge to pursue, vengeance He could savor.

Trouble once again finds him, to Daggerdale flees,
His heart and hands he puts to work, for a new light he sees.
Purity  desired, redemption  sought, for stains upon his soul, 
The force of good he seeks, to aid the Dales, for peace of heart his goal.

Sands did call to him once more, by chance did meet Bedine, 
Trust they give and peace he finds, acceptance, within their kind.
Finds some solace in desert gods, to them he learns to pray,
Feeling touched, by Elah's hand, praying in the dawns new day.

With gift in hand, returns to the 'Deep, a conflict to appease, 
Given then a task, though for friendships sake, chooses to not please.
Plots and plans He tries to do, still cannot carry through,
The East it calls him once again, to it he flees, to live and do.

There he lives for much time, meeting witches, in the sands,
Adventures, many does He find, keeping him from other lands.
Dreams of being a king someday, to power hold, the Blackroad rule,
His sworn enemy, the Zhentish horde, he wishes to de-jewel.

To Daggerdale his adventures lead, a brother, he finds there,
Then an evil lich, who just had to go, for in a tower he made his lair.
Unwitting, did fund his own demise by crowns filched from his coffers,
With an arrow pieced his throat, though a final unearthly howl he offers.

For his efforts , the Dales honors him, a warrant for to trade,
So He then starts, hoping with merchant ways, to put away his blade.
On return to the 'deep, Zhentish scum upon the road, does then chance to meet,
Accuse they him, of spying for the Dale-Lord, threats they do repeat.

A stone of power, masked Lords sought, so took up the task,
 Save the city, from the Masters threat to open the gate, they did ask.
A journey to Hell and back again, brought the stone to Faerun's land,
 Stolen was it once more, for profits gain, this time by a friends hand.

The lure of profit great, returned him to the 'Deep
Where immense responsibilities, are handed in a heap.
A trusted friend He found at last, then an unrequited love,
Balancing the weight of work, with orders from above.

To a Festival was he invited, dressed in velvet black,
There did witness competitions, of wit and word there was no lack.
 With mingled awe and dread, meets Silver Dragon and High Lady too,  
Then Melikki, did honor all, appeared ...... blessing the entire crew.

Many worries did follow him , as he went about his day,
To Gondalims, his feet took him, to some friends a visit pay.
In conversation deep they sat, there entered then a mage quite rude,
When nicely asked to close the door, the mage replied with remarks crude.

Warnings were given, by each side, though sadly unheeded went,
Fighting ensued, forgotten was caution, as anger they did vent.
The mage was powerful, quite so, a banshee's wail cast,
There did strike poor Jacho down, that breath it was his last.

Twenty-one years, my tale unfolds, some for each year of his life,
For one so young, he had his share, of trouble and of strife.
Many things in his life he did, some wrong, and some right,
But only the gods can judge him now, removed he is, from spite.

We, his friends, remember him for what he means to each,
Hold in our hearts, the memory, of all he had to teach.
Now my friends the tales done, nothing left to plan,
So raise your cups, toast with me, the life of a complex man!

Truth ... to him , was as plain as the scar down his jaw.

 Was left quite despairing when the man met his end .

He walked the knifes edge in bounds that he knew.

Who wore polished armor and carried a blade.

Proclaiming his love, thought she ignored his intent.

Tried to forget ..............by roaming the land.

Of him entering the halls of Tempus without shame.

And the rest of you, now know his story.
So all take a moment to remember the man,
He was a brother, a lover, a simple man of the clan.
